events.name: Android Fu
events.description:
http://photos3.meetupstatic.com/photos/event/b/2/9/a/event_83805722.jpegDo or do not. There is no try. --Yoda

Come out and work through a simple coding challenge. These are designed to be simple exercises that should provide a modest challenge, promote better design and produce functioning code. Whether you're brand new or a seasoned veteran there should be something to be learned.

 

The challenge will be created by an independent 3rd party (great idea Matt!)  The Android Code Monkey has graciously agreed to create a scalable challenge suitable for: NOVICE, INTERMEDIATE and ADVANCED Android developers.

 

Greg (aka Android Code Monkey) has been developing for Android since the original G1 device.  He has a number of personal and professional apps to his credit and enough grey hairs to adequately devise a challenge for varied skill levels.  He has been instructed to keep the details of the challenge a secret until the day, hopefully the hour, of the challenge.  I am very excited to see what he comes up with, but even more so to see all the different implementations of such!

 

Good luck and may the force be with you ... always!

events.description:
Free Tech Webinar on "What every product manager developing mobile apps should know - a deep down into product innovation."

Presenter: Boris Glants

Date & Time: Wednesday, July 25, 2012 - 01:00 PM - 02:00 PM PST

Registration: To register for this webinar. Visit: http://bit.ly/L7Zpaa

Webinar Highlights:

1. Understanding when you need to innovate.
2. What drives innovation: business demands or technology?
3. When to apply incremental or leap-frog innovation to your products?
4. How to systematically apply innovation to product development?
5. How to manage the innovation life-cycle?
6. Real-life examples of how innovation was achieved.

Presenter's Profile:

Boris is a seasoned technology focused entrepreneur. Over the past ten years, he has built multiple companies focused on web and mobile products. Currently he is the CTO of Tonic Solutions where he built the iPad platform for patient data collection that replaces the regular pen and paper used today. It?s being adopted by UCSF, UCLA, Duke and other major hospital systems in the US. He is also a technical adviser to www.60minutestrategicplan.com.

events.name: Boilerstrapping Usability for Android
events.description:
Boilerstrapping Usability for Android

This talk will be aimed at all levels of experience and interest. Mobile web development can be a gnarly beast from a code perspective, but how much time do you give to the experience the folks using your application will have? Boilerstrapping Usability for Android will give you some quick routes when "we've run out of time/budget" comes up in conversations about usability. Maybe you don't have a dedicated resource on your team… we'll go over some self-starter activities you can do yourself on a bar napkin… that is, if you choose that route. Maybe we'll spend the entire time looking at design conventions… or just complaining about why it took them so long to move to a consistent (ish) experience across devices. This presentation will be interactive in the style of the choose-your-own-adventure books of old, so show up ready to help steer because by the end, Chris prefers that the blame (err… success) is shared all around.

 

About Chris

Who is this Chris guy? He's an experience designer and interface developer for ThoughtWorks, a community of passionate individuals looking to do the best software design and delivery while advocating for positive social change along the way. He's a proponent of mobile-first thinking (when appropriate) and tries to close the loop between feedback, design, and development as close as the laws of physics will allow. He's been venturing around for the past few years working with startups and companies on MVP development, pivots, and other such things with an emphasis on Science and user input. Full disclosure: while born in Ohio, his sports allegiances lie with Cleveland.

One of the coolest (and possibly creepiest) things about our phone is that it usually knows where we are in the world based on our coordinates in the GPS (Global Positioning System).  With that data we can make our apps do some pretty cool things!  Geofences define a GPS point and a radius in meters to create "triggers" for action.  I will show you how to setup the Google Maps API and add geofences to any application.

About Bill Mote:
Bill was a lifelong infrastructure nerd with a passion for making things better, faster and more reliable.  The DevOps world just didn't give him enough heads down coding time so when Android hit the scene Bill decided to forgo his safety net and start developing for Android full time.  In addition to a handful of his own utility apps, Bill has built apps for startups and Fortune 50s alike with contributions to more than a dozen apps currently available in the Play Store.  Bill is the co-organizer of our Cincy Android Meetup as well as GDG Cincinnati and truly enjoys both the teachings and learnings he gets out of them.

Adding automated tests to your app can be daunting at first, but we will learn about the tools that are available when to use them, and what to avoid.

Patrick Hammond is a long-time Android developer, co-organizer of GDG Cincinnati, and a founding partner at Atomic Robot.  He enjoys spending time with his family, barbecue, bourbon, and coding late into the night.

Note: September’s presentation will be at Northern Kentucky University.

42 Things I Wish I Knew When I Started Android Development

If you’re an Android developer there are a ton of resources available to you, things everyone eventually learns the hard way, and tools to help you work smarter as an Android developer.  This discussion will be around at least 42 of the things Patrick has found useful, learned though embarrassing bugs, or wishes existed when he started developing Android apps.

Patrick Hammond is a long-time Android developer, co-organizer of GDG Cincinnati, and a founding partner at Atomic Robot.  He enjoys spending time with his family, barbecue, bourbon, and coding late into the night.

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation & Discussion: Realm
events.description:
Whether you’re an experienced Android developer, or you’re just getting started, you will need to think about storing data on the device. Android offers several options including relational data storage on a SQLite Database, but the APIs and examples provided by Google look like the state-of-the-art JDBC programming you did back in 1995! In this talk, you’ll learn how to use RealmDB, an elegant Object Relational database alternative to SQLite, to make database development on Android fun, easy, and testable.

Eric Maxwell is a Principal Engineer at Credible Software. He has spent 11 years architecting and developing software for various companies across different industries. His current focus is training, mentoring, and mobile development. He has developed and taught courses on Java, Android and iOS. When he’s not working he enjoys spending time with family, and watching/performing improv comedy. He is one of the founding members of Hashtag Comedy in Columbus and a cast member from[masked].

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation: Build a Santa Tracker App with Firebase
events.description:
With Christmas just a few days away we're going festive this month and will be creating an app that lets us track Santa as he flys across the world delivering presents to the good girls and boys who test their code.  We'll be starting with an empty Android project, add in Google Maps, and use Firebase to get Santa's location.

This will be an interactive, code lab style event so be prepared to have some fun coding and help each other out. Please come with a laptop with Android Studio already installed (get started here: <a>https://developers.android.com</a>;) and ideally either a device or working emulator.

Food and drinks will be provided.

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation: Be More Productive with Kotlin
events.description:
People are excited about developing Android applications with Kotlin.  From new side projects to existing enterprise level Java architectures, Kotlin can improve code quality and readability while reducing lines of code and eliminating entire classes of bugs.  Find out why Kotlin is being used by developers at companies like Square, Trello, and Pintrest.

Brandon Wever is a mobile developer at Atomic Robot and a recent graduate of NKU's Computer Science Graduate Program.  His number one goal in software is to find simple, pragmatic solutions and having tools that work for you. 

Food and drinks will be provided.

Google Participant Survey: http://goo.gl/GjbSNb

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation: Astronomer for Analytics in Android
events.description:
This month we will have Mike Perry from local Cincinnati startup, Astronomer, talk to us about how to integrate Astronomer into your Android app. 

Astronomer is building a platform that can ingest, process, and move data from any source to any destination. One source of data that Astronomer supports is clickstream data from apps and websites. Come learn how to get started with analytics-android and see how it can help you gather insights about your app's usage. 

Mike Perry started out as an iOS and Android developer at UC. He now works at Astronomer, where he's focused on Aries.js. Aries is an open source Node.js based framework for writing ETL pipelines. When not working on Aries, he's hacking on Airflow and other infrastructure services. 

Food and drinks will be provided.

Google Participant Survey: http://goo.gl/GjbSNb

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation & Discussion
events.description:
Bring a laptop this month as we'll be back in the Mason Tech Center classroom where Taron Foxworth from Losant will be leading an Internet of Things workshop!

The Losant IoT Hardware Workshop is a fun, hands-on, and interactive introduction to your first connected widget. The self-guided session provides all of the hardware, software, and instructions needed to build several simple connected experiences. The workshop is fun for all skill levels from novice to advanced developers.

Taron Foxworth is the Developer Evangelist at Losant. He translates technology for people to learn, love, and be inspired.

Losant will be providing the hardware for the workshop. Be sure to bring a laptop capable of running Arduino IDE (https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/Software). Please go to Losant's Environment Setup page and install the software before the meetup so we can get through the workshop on time!

Please be sure to RSVP so we can make sure to have enough hardware kits for everyone.

events.name: Realm World Tour Cincinnati
events.description:
Cincy CocoaHeads along with GDG Cincinnati and Atomic Robot will be hosting the Realm World Tour in Cincinnati.

Realm World Tour:

Our team is hitting the road! For the first time ever, we’ll be traveling to 23 cities, hosting free events throughout the US, Europe, and Asia. Attendees will get live demos of the new Realm Mobile Platform, extended Q&A time with folks at Realm, good food, great people, and of course some rockin’ swag. Space is limited, so register soon. Hope to see you there!

Please register for this event at Eventbrite; not on Meetup.

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/realm-world-tour-cincinnati-tickets-31339164284

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation: Android Things (and robots!)
events.description:
Android Things lets you build Android apps that run on devices like a Raspberry Pi using all of the great tools already available and familiar to Android developers. 

This discussion will be a deeper dive into how you can use the Android Things SDK to build apps that interact with the real world. Expect to see lots of live demos on devices.

Presenter: Patrick Hammond is a partner and mobile engineer at Atomic Robot and co-organizer of GDG Cincincinnati. He is a software guy who has recently learned how to have fun with electronics and is building up a collection of freshly fried circuit boards and servos.

Food and drinks will be provided.

events.name: Special Meetup: Firebase and Beyond:  Mobile backends on Google Cloud Platform
events.description: Currently using Firebase and wondering where you can go from here?  Looking for possibilities outside of a single framework?  Want to leverage PaaS and ML APIs for your app?  Phillip Knoll from the Google Cloud Platform team will be talking about how mobile developers can leverage GCP as a backend for their apps, including App Engine, Cloud functions and more.

events.name: Monthly Presentation: Android Instant Apps
events.description:
Android Instant Apps is a new feature that allows Android users to discover and use your native Android app without having to install it from Google Play.

This discussion will show you how to convert your native Android app (or a subset of it) into an Android Instant App. We will also talk about which use cases make for good instant apps and the current limitations for building an instant app.

Presenter: Greg Williams is an Android engineer at Dotloop (a Zillow Group company) and co-organizer of GDG Cincinnati. He and his team at Dotloop were part of Google's Android Instant App early adopter partnership. The Dotloop Instant App was featured at Google I/O. He will also talk a bit about what it was like working with Google as an early adopter.

Google Participant Survey: http://goo.gl/GjbSNb

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation & Discussion: Constraint Layout
events.description:
With ConstraintLayout 1.0 being announced earlier in the year are you wondering if you should dive head first into the world of flat view hierarchies? How easy is the Layout Editor to use, can views be chained together and what’s constraint bias? Join in a discussion lead by Adam Toennis, a developer at Atomic Robot, to answer these questions and more.

Google Participant Survey: http://goo.gl/GjbSNb

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation & Discussion: Lightning Talks!
events.description:
This month we will have several exciting lighting talks lined up!

#1) An introduction to Android’s Room Persistence Library. 
Kyle Couch is a Mobile Developer at LCS and is an Android/iOS enthusiast.

#2) I will be demonstrating a few basic BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy) techniques such as discovering if the current device supports Bluetooth LE, scanning for a Bluetooth LE device and continuously update the current RSSI (Received Signal Strength Indicator) value in a RecyclerView. Lastly, I will demonstrate how to connect to a BLE device and discover the device services and characteristics.
Jonathan Davis is a Mobile Developer at Valentine Research and is very familiar of the pains of Android’s BLE. He’s is primarily an Android Developer plans to branch into iOS development.

#3) We'll be going over a high-level introductory overview of VR development using Google Cardboard and Google Daydream. These platforms offer a great opportunity for getting started in the VR space and with a lower barrier to entry than other HMD systems.
Stuart Bowman is a Mobile Engineer at Atomic Robot who loves doing all things 3D, from Virtual Reality to 3D printing.

Google Participant Survey: http://goo.gl/GjbSNb

events.name: Monthly Android Developers Presentation & Discussion
events.description:
Google Cloud Platform (GCP) is a suite of modern, cutting edge, service offerings that enable developers to build robust and scalable applications. 

In this talk we'll take a wide look at the services GCP has to offer. The focus of the talk will be highlighting the higher level service offerings available in GCP such as Web Serving, Database, Machine Analytics, and Big Data services. 

About the Presenter: Wesley Workman is Software Architect at Batterii. He's spent the past 5 years building a cutting edge application on GCP at Batterii. Batterii is a collaborative platform built to assist users who are conducting design research and design thinking activities. 

Google Participant Survey: http://goo.gl/GjbSNb

events.name: Monthly Presentation: Actions on Google for the Google Assistant
events.description:
Update: Our October scheduled speaker has become ill so we're changing topics for this month.

"Ok Google, ...." is something that gets said more and more as people are finding new ways of interacting with their phones, watches, TVs, speakers, cars, and more! This month will be a quick introduction to Actions on Google and how you can quickly start building your first apps for the Google Assistant without needing to write a single line of code.

Presenter: Patrick Hammond is a partner and mobile engineer at Atomic Robot and co-organizer of GDG Cincinnati.

events.name: Build a Santa Tracker Android app in Kotlin powered by Firebase
events.description:
With Christmas just a few days away we're going festive this month and will be creating an Android app that lets us track Santa as he flies across the world delivering presents to good girls and boys who test their code.

As a group, we will start with an empty Android project, include Kotlin support, add in Google Maps, and then talk to a Firebase database to track Santa throughout the evening.

Previous experience building Android apps is not required to participate: this is an opportunity to learn how to get started building Android apps. This will be a code lab style event so you should be prepared to have fun coding, not be surprised if we run into a few bugs, and should encourage you to work together with the people sitting near you.

We do ask that you please bring your own laptop with Android Studio 3.0 (latest version) installed, downloads finished, and at least one project created and run on a device or emulator. You can follow along with this video to get things going:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z98hXV9GmzY

(and yes, we're aware that zombies are not especially festive this time of the year). If you run into problems getting things installed and setup, post a note in the comments so we can try to help you out before the event. This will help us ensure everyone has a great time and we are able to finish building the app on time. Food and drink will be provided.

events.name: Cloud Study Jam
events.description:
Want to get started on the Google Cloud, but don't know where to begin?

Join us for our Cloud Study Jam! Together we'll work through three Google Cloud Platform Essentials labs, then you will get free access to the next quest so you can finish this series of labs at home to get a Google-hosted badge for your online profile. You will be able to get hands-on experience with Docker, Kubernetes and Scientific Data Processing, which will earn you additional badges.

Join this meetup to get official Google training, a $70+ value, free of charge.

What do I need?
Bring a laptop (PC, Mac or Chromebook)! The labs will run on all of the latest versions of the popular browsers. For the best experience, make sure your laptop has Firefox or Chrome installed. Don't forget your power cord!

How long does it take?
One in-person session of 3 hours, followed by 2-8 hours of self-study.

What's the end result?
Google-hosted badges that attendees can use in their online profiles and show to employers.

We will be in the first floor classroom in the Mason Tech Center. Don't worry about dinner, food and drink will be provided!

events.name: Monthly Presentation: RxJava for Android
events.description:
Dan Pinciotti will show us how to use RxJava to replace asynchronous callbacks in an Android app.
Dan will start with a simple chat app that uses PubNub with lots of callbacks for doing the asynchronous calls. Then he will refactor the code to the RxJava way of doing asynchronous calls, replacing all the callbacks with RxJava. We'll see the advantages of RxJava for doing asynchronous computing, demonstrating quite a few Rx operators along the way.

Dan Pinciotti is the Android developer lead at Dotloop (a Zillow Group company).

events.name: Pi’s and Pints at Firehouse Grill
events.description:
Come celebrate Pi Day with the designers & app developers of Atomic Robot.

Connect with industry professionals, discuss the latest in mobile design & development, and, of course, enjoy food and drinks!

See you there!

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/pis-and-pints-mobile-dev-meetup-registration-43576831476

events.name: Using Network Cache for Fun and Profit
events.description:
You’re assigned a project which needs to pull down data and still function without connectivity. The project has millions and millions of users and you would prefer to limit the impact to the server. What do you do?!

Join Adam Toennis, a senior developer at Atomic Robot, as he discusses the usage of the Network Cache in Android applications.

Due to construction at the Atomic Robot office, we will again be downstairs in the classroom. Follow the Meetup signs!

events.name: Machine Learning Study Jam
events.description:
New to Machine Learning but don’t know where to start? Join us for a Machine Learning Study Jam! Brian and Jeffrey Bonner will lead us through the Machine Learning Crash Course (MLCC) from Google Developers!

This course is intended for those who wish to learn about ML from a practical, applied perspective that will enable you to use machine learning in your everyday projects and learn about the power of TensorFlow. This is a great opportunity for anyone with basic technical knowledge and limited Machine Learning knowledge willing to gain some practical experience in ML and TensorFlow.

**Bring your laptop with a current version of the Chrome browser! (version 58 or later)**

Agenda:
5:30pm: Meet & Greet and food provided
6:00pm: overview & first 3 modules of MLCC
7:45pm: break
8:00pm: TensorFlow modules
9:30pm: event end

We will be on the 1st floor of the Mason Tech Center again. Follow the meetup signs!
This is a bit longer than our normal meetup, so come early and we'll start promptly at 6pm!

events.description:
We will have a series of lightning talks from several attendees to go a little more in-depth on announcements from Google I/O along with some Q&A time at the end.

There will be I/O swag to give away!

Food and drinks provided by Atomic Robot.

events.name: Introduction to Mobile BAAS (Backend-As-A-Service)
events.description:
When you are working on a new project and you don’t have time to develop a custom backend for your application, you can use BAAS tools like Firebase, Kinvey or Dubtel. In this session, Sage Conger from DUBTEL will delve into the details of using these tools to speed up your application development process.

• Authentication
• CRUD Operations
• Dashboard Reports
• Push Notifications

Sage Conger is a Software Engineer at DUBTEL (https://dubtel.com) in West Chester, specializing in Mobile Application development and community support. Sage is a graduate of the Capital University majoring in Computer Science and Mathematics. Follow her on Twitter @CongerSage (https://twitter.com/CongerSage)

events.name: How to get started with Actions on Google Applications
events.description:
This week, Mai Truong will talk about Actions on Google (AoG) and what it can do. She will discuss the terminology, concepts, and tools for writing your own AoG application.

She will also demonstrate how to use DialogFlow to create an agent that can understand and parse user input and return responses. She will show how to access AoG's analytics information and logging, and where to find additional documentation.

About Mai: Mai Truong is a Software Engineering Co-op at Atomic Robot and a University of Cincinnati student majoring in Computer Science.

events.name: Kotlin isn't just for Android Development
events.description: Kotlin isn't just for Android development! It's a great new language that can be used anywhere you would use Java! So come listen to Michael Clark tell us what his team went through to evaluate the language, tooling and company culture before using Kotlin with Spring in their back-end.

events.name: Monthly GDG Cincinnati Presentation & Discussion: Rotor.ai
events.description: This month Stuart Bowman will share on his initial implementation of a self-driving car project, rotor.ai. We will cover the basics of connecting Bluetooth devices, using PWM to drive multiple motors, and getting an Android Things project "rolling". We will also take a look at the mobile app component of rotor.ai, including using elements from Android Jetpack, such as DataBinding and Live Data.

events.name: Build a Santa Tracker App using Flutter, Google Maps, and Firebase
events.description:
It's our annual Android holiday coding event! This year we will learn how to build a Santa Tracker app in Flutter using Google Maps and Firebase. Best of all: you will be able to track Santa on both Android and iOS! Previous Flutter experience is not required, but we do ask that you bring a laptop that can run Android Studio or XCode.

This event has been popular in previous years and we have limited seating. If you do RSVP and then are not able to attend we ask that you update your RSVP status so that someone else on the waitlist will be able to attend.

Food, drinks, and presents will be provided. Additional details on software to install will be provided the week of the event.

events.name: Using SQLite's Full Text Search (FTS) with Room on Android
events.description:
Full Text Search (FTS) is an extension for SQLite that allows users to perform full-text searches efficiently without using the inefficient LIKE clause. Room, Android's SQLite persistence library from JetPack, now supports FTS3 and FTS4 in version 2.1

This month, GDG Cincinnati co-organizer, Greg Williams, will show us how to use FTS with Room!

Participant survey link: https://goo.gl/Y8Y9Gu

events.name: March Madness with Firebase and JHipster
events.description:
Developing an app with Firebase's new real time database, Firestore, is quick and easy. However, using the Firebase console to maintain data once it goes live is probably not a best practice. In this presentation, Brian Telintelo will show how quickly you can create an admin interface by marrying the popular code generator JHipster, and the Firebase Firestore Admin SDK.

Brian is a senior mobile app developer at Atomic Robot. He prefers to do iOS development, but has been known to do Android on occasion.

events.name: Test Driven Development for Flutter
events.description:
Maybe you've heard about Google's new mobile UI framework called Flutter? This month is a chance to learn how to implement Test Driven Development (TDD) practices in your next Flutter app!

Topics we will cover include:
* How to write basic unit level tests in Dart
* Mocking out dependencies in tests
* Testing asynchronous calls in Dart (specifically working with Streams)
* Widget level testing
* Demo some helpful built-in tools for debugging Widget layouts at runtime.

Food and drinks will be provided.

events.name: Google I/O Extended 2019 Cincinnati: Lightning Talks!
events.description:
Google I/O will wrap up just a few days before this event and we know there will be some exciting announcements!

Instead of spending an evening diving into just one topic we're going to split this event into a few different 10-minute lightning talks on different announcements. Prior experience on a subject is not expected; just come curious.

To make this event a success, we need a few people who are willing to put together a short talk on something announced at I/O that you found interesting and why. The fun part is that you will have less than a week to prepare!

*** If you're interested in talking about something new that no one else has talked about or used yet, drop a note in the comments so we can add you to the schedule below! ***

Lightning Talks:
- Android Auto by Jonathan Davis
- View Binding by Sampada Kadam
- CameraX by Jason Meyer
- Jetpack Compose by Amanda Scheetz
- Android Studio 3.5 by Justin Scarbrough

Food and drinks will be provided.

events.name: Threading on Android with Kotlin Coroutines
events.description:
Threading on Android has been a hard problem since the start. From your first NetworkOnMainThreadException to a laggy RecyclerView, we’ve all had at least one threading issue in our apps. Kotlin recently introduced the newest way to simplify asynchronous programming with coroutines. Come learn how to jump off the main thread and jump back on in code without callbacks.

IMPORTANT! This month we're going to be at a different location: at Alchemy's office in downtown Cincinnati. The address is: 1100 Sycamore Street, 3rd floor. Enter from the Sycamore Street side. For parking, there's a few spaces at the office building on the Reading Road and Eggleston Ave side, on the street on Reading or Sycamore, the ParkHaus garage, or you can park for free at the Jack Casino.
